const a = [
  {"id":13226,"text":"A second year MBBS student performed experiments related to the sense of taste in the physiology lab. Which of the following taste sensation will have the lowest stimulation threshold?","explanation":"Among the five primary taste sensations (sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and umami), bitter taste sensation has the lowest stimulation threshold. This means that bitter substances can be detected at lower concentrations compared to other taste sensations.\r\n\r\nBitter taste receptors are typically more sensitive and can recognize a wide range of bitter compounds. This heightened sensitivity to bitterness is thought to have evolved as a protective mechanism against the ingestion of potentially toxic substances, as many bitter compounds are associated with toxicity in nature.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other taste sensations such as sweet, sour, salty, and umami have higher stimulation thresholds and require higher concentrations of specific substances to be perceived. Sweet taste is typically associated with sugars, sour taste with acidic substances, salty taste with the presence of ions, and umami taste with savory or protein-rich foods.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that individual variations in taste sensitivity can exist, and different individuals may have different thresholds for detecting specific taste sensations.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 676.","responses":[{"text":"Acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sweet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitter","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16194,"text":"Which muscle is pierced by the parotid duct?","explanation":"The **buccinator** muscle is a thin, flat muscle located in the cheek region. It plays a crucial role in functions such as blowing air, whistling, and, most importantly, keeping the cheek taut against the teeth during chewing and speaking. This muscle also assists in pushing food onto the grinding surface of the molars during mastication.\r\n\r\nThe parotid duct, also known as Stensen's duct, arises from the parotid gland, which is one of the major salivary glands located near the ear. This duct passes through the buccinator muscle to transport saliva from the parotid gland into the oral cavity. This unique arrangement allows saliva to be released into the mouth when we eat or initiate the process of digestion, aiding in the breakdown of food.","reference":"Wineski LE, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Anatomy by Regions. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 636.","responses":[{"text":"Buccinator","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomaticus major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16195,"text":"What is the refractive index of the lens?","explanation":"A refractive index of **1.40** indicates that the lens of the eye is highly effective at bending light, allowing it to focus incoming light rays precisely onto the retina, where photoreceptor cells capture visual information. Any alteration in the refractive index of the lens can affect a person's ability to see clearly and may require corrective measures such as eyeglasses or contact lenses to restore proper vision.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 638.","responses":[{"text":"1.00","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.40","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1.38","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.34","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.33","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16253,"text":"An 18-year-old man comes to the emergency department with the complaint of inability to completely open his mouth and numbness on his chin and gingiva on his lower jaw after a motorbike accident. On x-ray, diagnosis of fracture of symphysis menti is made. Which nerve is responsible for the numbness?","explanation":"The **inferior alveolar nerve** is a branch of the **mandibular division** of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V) and provides sensory innervation to the lower teeth, the chin, and the lower lip. In the case of a fracture of the **symphysis menti** (the midline junction of the mandible), the nerve can be compressed or injured, leading to numbness and loss of sensation in the distribution of the nerve.\r\n\r\nThis condition is often referred to as \"mental nerve anesthesia\" or \"inferior alveolar nerve anesthesia\" and can result from various types of trauma to the mandible, including fractures. It can cause temporary or, in some cases, long-term sensory disturbances in the affected area.","reference":"Ghatak RN, Helwany M, Ginglen JG. Anatomy, head and neck, mandibular nerve. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 21, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507820/","responses":[{"text":"Auricotemporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior alveolar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16255,"text":"A patient is brought into the emergency department after sustaining a gunshot wound in the temporal fossa. On examination, there is bleeding from the ear. CT scan reveals a fracture of the bony floor of the temporal fossa. Which clinically important structure lies in the floor of the temporal fossa?","explanation":"The **pterion** is a small, H-shaped area of the skull where several bones come together: the frontal bone, parietal bone, greater wing of the sphenoid bone, and the temporal bone. It is a critical landmark because the middle meningeal artery runs underneath it. In cases of trauma or injury to the temporal fossa, such as a fracture of the bony floor, damage to the middle meningeal artery can lead to an **epidural hematoma**. This is a medical emergency as the buildup of blood between the skull and the dura mater can put pressure on the brain and require immediate intervention. The bleeding from the ear in this patient is indicative of a potential temporal fossa injury involving the middle meningeal artery.","reference":"Muche A. Positions and types of pterion in adult human skulls: a preliminary study. Ethiop J Health Sci. 2021;31(4):875-884. doi:10.4314/ejhs.v31i4.23","responses":[{"text":"Asterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obelion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16256,"text":"A boy complains of loss of sensation from the anterior aspect of the tongue. In which nuclei of the brainstem does the nerve carrying the concerned sensation end?","explanation":"The sensation from the anterior aspect of the tongue is carried primarily by the chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve (CN VII), which conveys taste sensations. The nerve fibers carrying this sensation end in the **nucleus of tractus solitarius** in the brainstem.\r\n\r\nThe nucleus of tractus solitarius is a part of the medulla oblongata and is responsible for processing taste and visceral sensory information. Sensory fibers from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue for taste sensation synapse in this nucleus.","reference":"AbuAlrob MA, Tadi P. Neuroanatomy, nucleus solitarius. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 22, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549831/","responses":[{"text":"Nucleus of tractus solitaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior salivatory nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleus ambiguous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal nucleus of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Motor nucleus of facial","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16275,"text":"An athlete arrives at the emergency department with a dislocated jaw due to a fall injury while running. He complains of difficulty in swallowing and speaking. Reduction of the mandible is prescribed as a treatment plan. Which muscle initiates the depression of the dislocated bone?","explanation":"The **lateral pterygoid muscle** is one of the muscles of mastication and plays a crucial role in the movement of the temporomandibular joint (TMJ). It has two heads, the superior and inferior heads, which work together to help lower the mandible or jaw. When this muscle contracts, it pulls the head of the mandible forward and downward, allowing for depression of the jaw. This action is essential for functions such as opening the mouth widely, chewing, and swallowing.","reference":"Rathee M, Jain P. Anatomy, head and neck, lateral pterygoid muscle. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 23, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549799/","responses":[{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16276,"text":"A boxer comes to the emergency department due to a blowout fracture caused by a direct hard blow to his face by his opponent. The x-ray confirms a fracture of the orbital floor. Which nerve is most likely to be damaged due to the blowout?","explanation":"The **infraorbital nerve** is a branch of the **maxillary nerve**, which itself is a branch of the **trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V)**. This nerve provides sensory innervation to the lower eyelid, upper lip, and part of the cheek. It travels through the infraorbital foramen in the maxilla, and in the case of a blowout fracture, the fracture site can compress or damage the infraorbital nerve, leading to sensory deficits in the areas it innervates.","reference":"Wineski LE, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Anatomy by Regions. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 655.","responses":[{"text":"Supraorbital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supratrochlear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short ciliary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infraorbital","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16286,"text":"The infraorbital fissure is posteriorly between the maxilla and the greater wing of the sphenoid bone. Which fossa communicates with this fissure?","explanation":"The **pterygopalatine fossa** is an important anatomical space located in the skull, and it serves as a crossroads for various neural and vascular structures. This fossa is situated behind the maxilla and connects with the infratemporal fossa laterally and the nasal cavity medially through the sphenopalatine foramen.","reference":"Wineski LE, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Anatomy by Regions. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 667.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior cranial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infratemporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cranial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supratemporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16289,"text":"Second-year medical students were asked to expose the muscles of sub-occipital triangle on a cadaver. Which of the following muscles is likely to be found?","explanation":"In the dissection of the sub-occipital triangle on a cadaver, the students are likely to find the **Rectus capitis posterior** muscle. The sub-occipital triangle is a small region located at the back of the neck, underneath the occiput. The muscles that form the boundaries of this triangle are primarily involved in the movements and stabilization of the head.\r\n\r\nThe sub-occipital triangle is bounded by three muscles:\r\n1. Rectus capitis posterior major: Located at the medial boundary.\r\n2. Obliquus capitis superior: Forms the superolateral boundary.\r\n3. Obliquus capitis inferior: The inferolateral boundary.\r\n\r\nThe rectus capitis posterior minor muscle, closely associated with the rectus capitis posterior major, is also found within this region. These muscles are important for extending and rotating the head at the atlanto-occipital and atlanto-axial joints.","reference":"George T, Tadi P. Anatomy, head and neck, suboccipital muscles. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 23, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567762/","responses":[{"text":"Longus capitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus capitis posterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Scalene medius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator scapulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenius capitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16387,"text":"During rhinoplasty, an ENT surgeon needs to give an incision to the five layers of the external nose. In which of the following layers lie the muscles?","explanation":"In the external nose, the muscles are located in the **third** layer. The external nose is composed of five layers, and each layer has distinct components. The layers, in order from superficial to deep, are:\r\n\r\n1. Skin: The outermost layer, which varies in thickness and contains sebaceous glands, hair follicles, and sweat glands.\r\n2. Superficial fatty layer (subcutaneous tissue): This layer provides padding and contains a variable amount of fat.\r\n3. **Muscle layer**: This is the third layer, where the muscles of the nose are located. These muscles include the procerus, nasalis, and portions of the orbicularis oris. They play a role in the movement of the nostrils and the expression of emotions.\r\n4. Fibrous connective tissue: This layer provides structural support and contains blood vessels and nerves.\r\n5. Perichondrium/periosteum: The deepest layer, covering the nasal cartilages and bones, providing nutrition and support.","reference":"Kim TK, Jeong JY. Surgical anatomy for Asian rhinoplasty. Archives of Craniofacial Surgery. Published June 20, 2019. Accessed June 28, 2023. http://e-acfs.org/journal/view.php?doi=10.7181/acfs.2019.00290","responses":[{"text":"Third","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Forth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fifth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16392,"text":"A 25-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a stab wound in the neck region directed into the submandibular triangle with tongue deviation. Which of the following nerves was damaged?","explanation":"The **hypoglossal nerve** (cranial nerve XII) is responsible for motor innervation to the muscles of the tongue. \r\n\r\nWhen the hypoglossal nerve is damaged or injured, it leads to weakness or paralysis of the tongue muscles on the same side as the injury. This results in the tongue deviating towards the injured side when protruded, due to unopposed action of the contralateral genioglossus muscle. The submandibular triangle is an anatomical region where the hypoglossal nerve is relatively superficial and thus susceptible to injury from trauma such as a stab wound.\r\n\r\nThe accessory nerve controls the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles; the facial nerve controls the muscles of facial expression; the trigeminal nerve is mainly responsible for facial sensation and motor functions in the jaw; and the glossopharyngeal nerve has roles in taste, swallowing, and salivation.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 999-1000.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigeminal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16419,"text":"What is the action of the superior oblique muscle on the eyeball?","explanation":"The action of the superior oblique muscle on the eyeball is **abduction, intorsion, and depression**. The superior oblique muscle is one of the six extraocular muscles that control the movement of the eyeball. It originates from the sphenoid bone and passes through a fibrocartilaginous loop called the trochlea before inserting onto the superolateral aspect of the eye.\r\n\r\nWhen the superior oblique muscle contracts, it primarily causes the eyeball to move downward (depression) and outward (abduction). Additionally, it causes intorsion, which is the inward rotation of the eyeball. The unique path of the superior oblique, particularly its action through the trochlea, facilitates these specific movements.\r\n\r\nThis muscle's actions are particularly effective when the eye is adducted (turned toward the nose), as its role in depression and intorsion becomes more pronounced in this position.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1065.","responses":[{"text":"Adduction, intorsion, and depression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adduction, extorsion, and depression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction, intorsion, and depression","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction, extorsion, and elevation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adduction, intorsion, and elevation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16420,"text":"Which movement of the eyeball will occur when the superior rectus and inferior oblique contract together?","explanation":"When the superior rectus and inferior oblique muscles of the eyeball contract together, the resulting movement is **elevation**. The superior rectus muscle primarily functions to elevate the eye (move it upward) and also contributes to adduction and intorsion. The inferior oblique muscle, while its primary action is extorsion (outward rotation) of the eye, also assists in elevation and abduction of the eyeball when the eye is in an adducted position.\r\n\r\nThe combined action of these two muscles primarily leads to the elevation of the eyeball. While each muscle has additional individual actions, their shared action in elevating the eye is predominant when they contract simultaneously.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 904.","responses":[{"text":"Elevation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intorsion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depression","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16423,"text":"Which movement of the eyeball will occur when the inferior rectus and superior oblique contract together?","explanation":"When the inferior rectus and superior oblique muscles of the eye contract together, the resulting movement of the eyeball is **Depression**. The inferior rectus muscle primarily functions to move the eye downward (depression) and slightly adducts the eye. On the other hand, the superior oblique muscle also contributes to depression, especially when the eye is in an adducted position, and it causes intorsion (inward rotation) of the eye.\r\n\r\nThe combined action of these two muscles leads to the depression of the eyeball. While each muscle has additional individual actions (such as adduction by the inferior rectus and intorsion by the superior oblique), their shared action in depressing the eye is predominant when they contract together.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 904.","responses":[{"text":"Depression","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intorsion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16440,"text":"The pterygopalatine fossa communicates with the middle cranial fossa through which of the following passages?","explanation":"The communication between the pterygopalatine fossa and the middle cranial fossa occurs through the **foramen rotundum**. This foramen is a passageway located in the sphenoid bone.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a small, pyramid-shaped space in the skull, situated posterior to the maxilla and below the apex of the orbit. It contains various important structures, including the pterygopalatine ganglion and branches of the maxillary nerve (V2), which pass through the foramen rotundum to reach the middle cranial fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 835.","responses":[{"text":"Pterygomaxillary fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenopalatine foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior orbital fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatovaginal canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen rotundum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16441,"text":"Olfactory epithelium can get damaged by inhalation of toxic fumes and causes physical injury to the nose by the use of nasal spray. What can this lead to?","explanation":"**Anosmia** is the loss or impairment of the sense of smell, and it can occur due to various factors, including inhalation of toxic fumes or physical injury to the nose, such as from the improper use of nasal sprays.\r\n\r\nWhen the olfactory epithelium is damaged, the sensory receptors responsible for detecting odors are affected, leading to a reduced or complete loss of the sense of smell. This can have several consequences, including:\r\n\r\n1. **Reduced appetite:** Anosmia can lead to a diminished ability to taste food, which may result in a decreased appetite or anorexia in some individuals.\r\n\r\n2. **Difficulty detecting hazards:** Loss of the sense of smell can make it challenging to detect potential dangers, such as spoiled food or gas leaks, which can have safety implications.\r\n\r\n3. **Impact on overall well-being:** Anosmia can affect one's quality of life, as the sense of smell plays a significant role in our perception of the environment and enjoyment of food and beverages.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"Insomnia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anosmia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diplopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anorexia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16442,"text":"Which nerve supplies the platysma muscle?","explanation":"The **cervical branch of the facial nerve** supplies the **platysma muscle**. \r\n\r\nThe platysma muscle is a thin, sheet-like muscle located in the neck region. It extends from the upper chest to the lower face and is involved in various movements of the neck and lower jaw. Contraction of the platysma muscle can produce expressions like tension in the neck, pulling down the corners of the mouth, or wrinkling the skin of the neck.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 853.","responses":[{"text":"Mandibular branch of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branch of glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branch of accessory spinal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical branch of facial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Branch of vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16444,"text":"Which nerve lesion results in contralateral motor loss of the inferior half of the face?","explanation":"A lesion of the **Corticobulbar** (or **Corticonuclear**) tract results in contralateral motor loss of the inferior half of the face. The corticobulbar tract originates in the motor cortex and projects to various cranial nerve nuclei in the brainstem. It primarily controls the voluntary muscles of the face and neck.\r\n\r\nIn the facial nucleus (which controls facial expression muscles), the upper part of the face receives bilateral corticobulbar innervation, meaning both hemispheres of the brain provide input. However, the lower part of the face receives predominantly contralateral innervation. Therefore, a lesion in the corticobulbar tract of one hemisphere typically leads to weakness or paralysis of the lower half of the face on the opposite side.","reference":"K, Daly DT. Neuroanatomy, lower motor neuron lesion. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539814/","responses":[{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticonuclear","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticospinal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16445,"text":"A newborn may present with caput succedaneum, leading to prolonged labor. The swelling is present in which layer of the scalp?","explanation":"**Caput succedaneum** is a common condition seen in newborns resulting from pressure on the infant's head during the birth process. It presents as swelling or edema of the soft tissues in the newborn's scalp. This swelling is present in the **connective tissue and aponeurosis layers** of the scalp.\r\n\r\nThe **scalp** itself is composed of several layers, including the skin, connective tissue, aponeurosis (also known as the galea aponeurotica), loose areolar tissue, and periosteum. During a prolonged labor or when there is pressure on the infant's head as it passes through the birth canal, the soft tissues in the scalp can become compressed, leading to the development of caput succedaneum.","reference":"Jacob K, Hoerter JE. Caput succedaneum. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK574534/","responses":[{"text":"Scalp and periosteum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aponeurosis and areolar tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Connective tissue and aponeurosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Loose areolar tissue and pericranium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin and connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16446,"text":"Which type of salivary gland secretes thin, watery, and rich in enzyme fluid only?","explanation":"The **parotid gland** is one of the major salivary glands located near the ear, and it is known for its production of a thin and watery saliva that is particularly rich in enzymes, particularly **amylase**. Amylase is an enzyme that plays a crucial role in the initial digestion of carbohydrates in the oral cavity.\r\n\r\nThe parotid gland is primarily responsible for the production of this enzyme-rich saliva, which aids in the breakdown of starches and facilitates the initial stages of food digestion.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 329.","responses":[{"text":"Von Ebners","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glands of palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16448,"text":"Which nerve passes through the root of the neck?","explanation":"The nerve that passes through the root of the neck is the **vagus nerve**. The vagus nerve, or cranial nerve X, is a critical nerve that extends from the brainstem through the neck and into the chest and abdomen. In the root of the neck, it descends between the internal carotid artery and the internal jugular vein, within the carotid sheath.\r\n\r\nThe vagus nerve has a wide range of functions, as it is a major component of the parasympathetic nervous system. It supplies motor parasympathetic fibers to most of the thoracic and abdominal viscera, and it also carries sensory and taste information from the root of the tongue and the pharynx. Additionally, it plays a role in controlling the muscles for voice and speech.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1016.","responses":[{"text":"Accessory cranial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibulocochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16449,"text":"Which of the following structures is a prominent feature of the lateral wall of the middle ear cavity?","explanation":"A prominent feature of the lateral wall of the middle ear cavity is the **epitympanic recess**. The epitympanic recess, also known as the attic, is an upper extension of the middle ear cavity situated above the level of the tympanic membrane. It houses important structures, including part of the malleus and incus, two of the three auditory ossicles.\r\n\r\nThe lateral wall of the middle ear, which forms part of the tympanic cavity, is largely occupied by the tympanic membrane. The epitympanic recess is situated superior to this membrane and plays a crucial role in the conduction of sound vibrations from the tympanic membrane to the inner ear through the ossicles.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 967.","responses":[{"text":"Canal for the tensor tympani muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aditus to mastoid antrum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidal process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epitympanic recess","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial canal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16450,"text":"The medial wall of the pterygopalatine fossa has which of the following opening?","explanation":"The **sphenopalatine foramen** is a crucial anatomical structure located in the medial wall of the pterygopalatine fossa. This foramen serves as a passageway for important structures, including the **sphenopalatine artery** and the **nasopalatine nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe **sphenopalatine artery** is responsible for supplying blood to various structures within the nasal cavity, including the nasal septum and the mucous membranes. The **nasopalatine nerve** carries sensory information from the nasal septum and the hard palate.","reference":"Cappello ZJ, Potts KL. Anatomy, pterygopalatine fossa. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 29, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513269/","responses":[{"text":"Foramen rotundum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygomaxillary fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenopalatine foramen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygoid canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior orbital fissure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16453,"text":"Histological features of an organ demonstrated mucosa lined by stratified squamous nonkeratinized epithelium with papillae. The core of the organ is of skeletal muscles. Which of the following organ matches this description?","explanation":"The histological features described, including mucosa lined by **stratified squamous nonkeratinized epithelium with papillae** and a core of skeletal muscles, are characteristic of the **tongue**. \r\n\r\nThe tongue is a muscular organ located in the oral cavity. The surface of the tongue is covered by stratified squamous nonkeratinized epithelium, which contains numerous papillae. These papillae house taste buds, which are responsible for taste sensation. The underlying core of the tongue consists of skeletal muscles, which are essential for its movements, such as speech, swallowing, and manipulation of food.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 298.","responses":[{"text":"Pharynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hard palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Soft palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatine tonsils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tongue","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16454,"text":"In a histology practical, some students were asked a question regarding a major salivary gland of pure serous nature. Trauma to that salivary gland causes damage to the nerve resulting in the loss of a section of the muscle of facial expression. Which nerve is involved?","explanation":"The nerve responsible for innervating the parotid gland and the muscles of facial expression is the **Facial nerve (Cranial Nerve VII)**. It is a mixed nerve that carries both motor and sensory fibers and plays a vital role in facial expression, taste sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, and salivary gland control, including the parotid gland.","reference":"Wineski LE, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Anatomy by Regions. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 855.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occulomotor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16455,"text":"A histopathologist was observing a slide of a gland under the microscope. It had darkly stained acini with the apical portion of cells filled with secretory granules with striated ducts. Which gland was being observed by the histopathologist?","explanation":"The histopathologist's description of darkly stained acini with the apical portion of cells filled with secretory granules and striated ducts corresponds to the **parotid gland**, which is one of the major salivary glands.\r\n\r\nThe Parotid gland is known for its serous acini, which produce a serous type of saliva rich in enzymes, particularly amylase. The dark staining of the acini is due to the presence of numerous secretory granules containing these enzymes. The apical portion of the cells is packed with these secretory granules.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 331.","responses":[{"text":"Sublingual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16456,"text":"While observing the microscopic features of the tongue, which of the following papillae is thread-like, deficient in taste buds, and present on the superior surface of the tongue?","explanation":"When observing the microscopic features of the tongue, the thread-like papillae that are deficient in taste buds and present on the superior surface of the tongue are called **filiform papillae**.\r\n\r\nFiliform papillae are the most numerous type of papillae on the tongue, and their primary function is not related to taste perception. Instead, they play a crucial role in providing friction and texture to the tongue's surface, which aids in activities such as manipulating food and facilitating speech.\r\n\r\nThese papillae have a pointed, thread-like appearance and do not contain taste buds, distinguishing them from other types of papillae found on the tongue. Taste buds are primarily associated with **Fungiform**, **Vallate**, and **Foliate papillae**, which are responsible for different aspects of taste perception.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 299, 326.","responses":[{"text":"Vallate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fungiform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Circumvallate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Filiform","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Foliate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16460,"text":"Meibomian glands are modified sebaceous glands present on which layer of the eyelid?","explanation":"Meibomian glands, also known as tarsal glands or meibomian follicles, are specialized sebaceous glands located within the **tarsal plate** of the eyelid. These glands play a crucial role in maintaining the health of the eye and the quality of tears.\r\n\r\nThe tarsal plate is a dense connective tissue structure within the eyelid that provides support and maintains the shape of the eyelid. Meibomian glands are embedded within this plate, and they secrete an oily substance called meibum. Meibum is an essential component of the tear film that helps prevent the evaporation of tears and maintains the lubrication of the eye's surface.\r\n\r\nDysfunction or blockage of Meibomian glands can lead to conditions such as **Meibomian gland dysfunction (MGD)**, which can result in dry eye syndrome and other ocular surface problems.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 508.","responses":[{"text":"Epidermis of skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dermis of skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tarsal plate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucous layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscular layer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16461,"text":"The cancer of the submandibular gland has involved a duct lined by low columnar secretory cells having multiple mitochondria at the base. Also, the duct involved is intralobular. Which of the following ducts is involved?","explanation":"The duct involved in the described case of submandibular gland cancer, which is lined by low columnar secretory cells with multiple mitochondria at the base and is intralobular, is the **striated duct**. Striated ducts are a component of the salivary gland ductal system and are characterized by their distinctive striations, which are due to the presence of numerous mitochondria in the basal parts of the cells.\r\n\r\nThese striations are actually infoldings of the basal plasma membrane, coupled with elongated mitochondria, which give the ducts their characteristic appearance. The primary function of striated ducts is to modify the saliva secreted by the gland by reabsorbing sodium ions and secreting potassium and bicarbonate ions, thereby playing a role in electrolyte and fluid balance in saliva.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 330.","responses":[{"text":"Intercalated duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excretory duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interlobular duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Striated ducts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16462,"text":"Which of the following layers of the cornea cannot regenerate, leading to corneal scarring?","explanation":"In the cornea, **Bowman's membrane** is the layer that cannot regenerate, and its damage can lead to corneal scarring. Bowman's membrane, also known as the anterior limiting membrane, is a tough layer found between the corneal epithelium and the stroma. It is composed of strong collagen fibers.\r\n\r\nWhen Bowman's membrane is injured, it cannot regenerate or repair itself. As a result, any injury to this layer often leads to scarring. This scarring can interfere with the clarity of the cornea, affecting vision by distorting or blocking the passage of light through the cornea to the retina.","reference":"Sridhar MS. Anatomy of cornea and ocular surface. Indian Journal of Ophthalmology. Published February 2018. Accessed June 30, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5819093/","responses":[{"text":"Endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descemets membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowman's membrane","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16463,"text":"A patient is seen in the neurosurgery clinic with an MRI confirmed pituitary adenoma. Surgical resection of the adenoma is planned. When considering the surgical approach, which paranasal sinus provides access to the pituitary gland?","explanation":"When planning surgical resection of a pituitary adenoma, the paranasal sinus that provides access to the pituitary gland is the **sphenoid sinus**. This sinus is located deep within the skull, posterior to the nasal cavity, and directly adjacent to the pituitary gland.\r\n\r\nAccess to the pituitary gland through the sphenoid sinus is achieved via a surgical procedure called **transsphenoidal surgery**. In this approach, a surgeon enters the sphenoid sinus through the nasal passages, creating a path to reach the pituitary gland without the need for external incisions. This minimally invasive technique is commonly used for the removal of pituitary tumors, as it allows for direct access to the gland while avoiding more extensive cranial procedures.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 960-961.","responses":[{"text":"Frontal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior ethmoidal air cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle ethmoidal air cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenoid sinus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16464,"text":"A patient complains of frontal sinus pressure. You determine that it is an infection and administer mucosal shrinking medication. The mucous will then drain into the nasal cavity through which of the following?","explanation":"When a patient experiences frontal sinus pressure due to an infection, the administration of mucosal shrinking medication can help relieve the condition. This medication reduces the swelling of the nasal mucosa, allowing for the drainage of mucus and the resolution of symptoms.\r\n\r\nThe mucous from the frontal sinus will drain into the nasal cavity through the **semilunar hiatus**. The semilunar hiatus is a key anatomical structure in the nasal cavity, located under the middle nasal concha. It serves as a passageway for the drainage of mucus from the frontal and maxillary sinuses into the nasal cavity.\r\n\r\nBy administering mucosal shrinking medication, you can facilitate the proper drainage of mucus from the affected sinus into the nasal cavity, relieving the patient's frontal sinus pressure and helping them recover from the infection.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 960.","responses":[{"text":"Nasolacrimal duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spheno-ethmoidal recess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenopalatine canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Semilunar hiatus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16465,"text":"Which of the following veins is not a tributary of the pterygoid venous plexus?","explanation":"The Maxillary vein is **not** a tributary of the pterygoid venous plexus. The pterygoid venous plexus is a network of veins located in the **pterygopalatine fossa**, which is an anatomical region within the skull. It receives blood from various sources within the head and face.\r\n\r\nThe other veins mentioned, including the **Sphenopalatine vein, Pharyngeal vein, Greater palatine vein, and Infraorbital vein**, are all tributaries or contributors to the pterygoid venous plexus.\r\n\r\n- The **Sphenopalatine vein** drains blood from the nasal cavity and the sphenoid sinus.\r\n- The **Pharyngeal vein** receives blood from the pharynx and communicates with the pterygoid venous plexus.\r\n- The **Greater palatine vein** drains the hard palate.\r\n- The **Infraorbital vein** collects blood from the lower eyelid and upper lip.","reference":"Golub B, Bordoni B. Neuroanatomy, Pterygoid Plexus. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed December 28, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555896/","responses":[{"text":"Infraorbital vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenopalatine vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater palatine vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary vein","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16490,"text":"Which pharyngeal arches are the middle ear ossicles derived from?","explanation":"The middle ear ossicles, which include the malleus, incus, and stapes, are derived from the **1st and 2nd pharyngeal arches** during embryonic development. \r\n\r\nThe malleus, commonly known as the hammer, and the incus, known as the anvil, develop from the first pharyngeal arch. The stapes, often referred to as the stirrup, originates from the second pharyngeal arch.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 286-287.","responses":[{"text":"4th and 6th","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd and 6th","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd and 4th","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd and 3rd","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st and 2nd","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16492,"text":"Failure of fusion of which of the following causes unilateral oblique cleft lip?","explanation":"A unilateral oblique cleft lip results from the **failure of fusion of the maxillary prominence with the medial nasal prominence**. During embryonic development, the face forms from the fusion of several prominences: the frontonasal prominence, two maxillary prominences, and two mandibular prominences.\r\n\r\nThe upper lip is formed by the fusion of the medial nasal prominences (which form the philtrum and central part of the upper lip) and the maxillary prominences (which form the lateral parts of the upper lip). When there is a failure of fusion between the maxillary prominence on one side and the corresponding medial nasal prominence, it results in a unilateral cleft lip. This cleft can range from a small notch in the vermilion border of the lip to a complete separation extending into the nasal floor and the primary palate.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 305.","responses":[{"text":"Frontonasal prominence with maxillary prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two medial nasal prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence with lateral nasal prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two mandibular prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence with medial nasal prominence","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16494,"text":"Which part does the sensory retina develop from?","explanation":"The sensory retina develops from the **pars optica retinae** during embryonic development. The pars optica retinae is the portion of the retina that contains the photoreceptor cells, which are responsible for detecting light and initiating the process of vision. \r\n\r\nDuring embryogenesis, the retina develops from the optic cup, which is derived from the diencephalon of the brain. The optic cup forms two layers: an outer layer and an inner layer. The inner layer develops into the neural retina or pars optica retinae, which contains the light-sensitive rod and cone cells, as well as other neural elements necessary for processing visual information.\r\n\r\nThe outer layer of the optic cup gives rise to the retinal pigment epithelium, which is crucial for the maintenance and function of the photoreceptor cells.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 362.","responses":[{"text":"Pars ciliaris retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars optica retinae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Outer layer of optic cup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars ividica retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars ceca retinae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16495,"text":"What is the visual faculty that allows us to take in information about space in three dimensions (3D)?","explanation":"The visual faculty that allows us to take in information about space in three dimensions (3D) is **stereopsis**. Stereopsis, often referred to as depth perception, is the ability to perceive the world in three dimensions and to understand the spatial relationships between objects in the visual field. This ability is largely dependent on having two eyes with overlapping fields of vision (binocular vision), which provide slightly different views of the same object.\r\n\r\nThe brain fuses these slightly disparate images from each eye, a phenomenon known as binocular disparity, to create a single three-dimensional image. This process enables us to judge distances and the relative position of objects in space more accurately than with one eye alone (monocular vision).\r\n\r\nWhile binocular vision is necessary for stereopsis, it is not synonymous with it. Stereognosis refers to the ability to perceive and recognize the form of an object in the absence of visual cues, primarily using tactile information. Visual acuity is the clarity or sharpness of vision, and the field of vision pertains to the entire area that can be seen without moving the eyes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 635","responses":[{"text":"Binocular vision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stereopsis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Visual acuity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stereognosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Field of vision","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16496,"text":"A man in his fifties presents with throbbing eye discomfort, a red eye, headache, and blurred vision. The intraocular pressure was at 60 mmHg, and the opthalmologist suspected glaucoma. What level of intraocular pressure would protect the optic nerve and halt eyesight loss?","explanation":"In the context of glaucoma, an intraocular pressure (IOP) of **15 mmHg** is generally considered the level that would help protect the optic nerve and prevent eyesight loss. Glaucoma is a group of eye conditions characterized by increased intraocular pressure, which can damage the optic nerve and lead to vision loss if left untreated.\r\n\r\nWhile the normal range of intraocular pressure can vary slightly among individuals, an IOP of 15 mmHg is often used as a reference point for an ideal pressure that minimizes the risk of optic nerve damage. However, it's important to note that individual factors, such as the thickness of the cornea and the overall health of the eye, can influence the tolerance to elevated IOP.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 636.","responses":[{"text":"30 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15 mmHg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"10 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16498,"text":"A fourth grader complained that he could not see the board from the back of the classroom. His eyes were checked by an opthalmologist after his mother took him to have any refractive issues corrected. What was the ultimate diagnosis, and which lens was given for correction?","explanation":"The ultimate diagnosis for the fourth grader who could not see the board from the back of the classroom is myopia, commonly known as **nearsightedness**, and the corrective lenses prescribed are **concave lenses.**\r\n\r\nMyopia is a refractive error where distant objects appear blurry while close objects can be seen clearly. This condition occurs when the eyeball is too long relative to the focusing power of the cornea and lens, causing light rays to focus at a point in front of the retina, rather than directly on its surface. \r\n\r\nTo correct this refractive error, concave (diverging) lenses are used in eyeglasses. These lenses help in diverging the light rays before they enter the eye, so they can be focused on the retina, thereby clearing up the vision for distant objects.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 632-633.","responses":[{"text":"Near sightedness and gave spherical lenses for correction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperopia and gave concave lenses for correction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myopia and gave spherical lenses for correction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Far sightedness and gave spherical lenses for correction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Near sightedness and gave concave lenses for correction","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16500,"text":"A patient visits the outpatient department due to ongoing headache symptoms. He claims to be experiencing visual issues, including an inability to see what is coming from the side. This resulted in the suspension of his driving privileges. Based on the information provided, his condition is described as which of the following?","explanation":"**Bitemporal hemianopia** is a specific type of visual field defect characterized by the loss of vision in the outer (temporal) half of the visual field of both eyes. In other words, the patient experiences a bilateral loss of peripheral vision from the sides, making it challenging to perceive objects approaching from the periphery.\r\n\r\nThis condition is often associated with lesions or compression of the **optic chiasm**, which is the point where the optic nerves from each eye partially cross. In cases of bitemporal hemianopia, the lesions typically affect the crossing fibers carrying information from the nasal (inner) visual fields of both eyes.","reference":"Yoshihara MK, Lui F. Neuroanatomy, bitemporal hemianopsia. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 1, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545213/","responses":[{"text":"Homonymous hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitemporal hemianopia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Binasal hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised intraocular pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral lesion of optic tract","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16501,"text":"In a fraction of a second, after rhodopsin has absorbed light energy, it begins to degrade. Which of these is the immediate product?","explanation":"After rhodopsin absorbs light energy, the immediate product of its degradation is **Bathorhodopsin**. Rhodopsin, a visual pigment in the rods of the retina, undergoes a series of rapid changes when exposed to light. This process is part of the phototransduction pathway, which converts light into electrical signals in the retina.\r\n\r\nWhen light hits rhodopsin, it causes a conformational change in its chromophore, 11-cis-retinal, converting it to all-trans-retinal. The first step in this series of changes involves the formation of bathorhodopsin. This is a very rapid process, occurring in just a few picoseconds after the absorption of light. Bathorhodopsin then undergoes further transformations through several intermediates, including lumirhodopsin, metarhodopsin I, and metarhodopsin II, eventually leading to the activation of the G-protein transducin and the subsequent cascade that results in the hyperpolarization of rod cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 642.","responses":[{"text":"Metarhodopsin-I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bathorhodopsin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lumirhodopsin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scotopsin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metarhodopsin-II","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16507,"text":"Which of the following cells sends inhibitory signals backward to regulate the lateral spread of visual signals to neighboring cells to help control the degree of contrast in the visual image?","explanation":"In the regulation of the lateral spread of visual signals and controlling the degree of contrast in the visual image, the **Interplexiform cell** plays a key role by sending inhibitory signals backward. Interplexiform cells are a type of neuron found in the retina that connect the inner and outer synaptic layers. Their primary function is to provide feedback from the inner to the outer retina.\r\n\r\nInterplexiform cells receive input from amacrine cells and send feedback signals to horizontal cells. This feedback mechanism is crucial for regulating the lateral spread of visual signals. By sending inhibitory signals to horizontal cells, interplexiform cells help modulate the activity of photoreceptors and bipolar cells. This process enhances the visual contrast and sharpness, making it easier to discern edges and contours in the visual field.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 646.","responses":[{"text":"Ganglion cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bipolar cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amacrine cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Horizontal cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interplexiform cell","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16508,"text":"Which neurotransmitter is released by rods and cones at their synapses with bipolar cells?","explanation":"Rods and cones, the photoreceptor cells in the retina, release the neurotransmitter **glutamate** at their synapses with bipolar cells in response to the absorption of light.\r\n\r\nWhen light strikes the photoreceptor cells, it triggers a series of biochemical events that result in the release of glutamate from the photoreceptor cell synapses. This release of glutamate is the initial step in the visual signal transduction pathway. \r\n\r\nThe glutamate released by photoreceptor cells, specifically rods and cones, serves as an excitatory neurotransmitter that activates bipolar cells. These bipolar cells further transmit the visual signals to ganglion cells, which then transmit the information to the brain via the optic nerve.","reference":"Shichi H. Physiological background. Basic Neurochemistry: Molecular, Cellular and Medical Aspects. 6th edition. Published 1999. Accessed July 2, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK28019/","responses":[{"text":"GABA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16509,"text":"Once presbyopia has set in, each eye maintains a fixed focus at a nearly constant distance which is unique to the individual's eye anatomy. Which of the following lenses would be the best for a person of advanced age to use to ensure clear vision at all distances?","explanation":"In presbyopia, the eye's ability to focus on objects at different distances, especially up close, diminishes due to age-related changes in the flexibility of the eye's lens. To ensure clear vision at all distances, including both near and far, individuals with presbyopia often benefit from **bifocal lenses**.\r\n\r\nBifocal lenses incorporate two different optical powers into a single lens. The upper part of the lens is designed for distant vision (typically corrected for myopia), while the lower part contains the prescription for close-up or reading vision. This allows individuals to switch between the two portions of the lens, depending on the distance of the object they are looking at.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 631.","responses":[{"text":"Cylindrical lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bifocal lens","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spherical lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biconvex lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biconcave lens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16510,"text":"Which of the following sensory modalities is conveyed by free nerve endings?","explanation":"Free nerve endings are responsible for conveying the sensory modality of **temperature**. These nerve endings, also known as thermoreceptors, are abundant in the skin and mucous membranes throughout the body.\r\n\r\nFree nerve endings can detect both **warmth** and **cold** sensations. When these nerve endings are stimulated by changes in temperature, they generate electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain, allowing us to perceive temperature variations in our environment.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 622.","responses":[{"text":"Smell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taste","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temperature","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16511,"text":"Which of the following factors is accountable for the emotions and memories linked to the sense of smell?","explanation":"Emotions and memories linked to the sense of smell are primarily attributed to the **Olfactory cortex**. The olfactory cortex is a region in the brain located in the **temporal lobe** and is responsible for processing and interpreting olfactory information (smell).\r\n\r\nWhen we encounter different smells, the olfactory receptors in our nose send signals to the olfactory bulb and then to the olfactory cortex. This region of the brain is intricately connected to the limbic system, particularly the **amygdala**, which is strongly associated with emotions and emotional memory.\r\n\r\nThis close connection between the olfactory cortex and the limbic system is why certain smells can evoke powerful emotions and vivid memories. The **limbic system** plays a crucial role in emotional processing and the formation of long-lasting memories, and the olfactory cortex's connections to this system make it a key player in the sensory experience of smell and its emotional and memory-related aspects.","reference":"Herz RS. The role of odor-evoked memory in psychological and physiological health. Brain Sciences. Published July 19, 2016. Accessed July 2, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5039451/","responses":[{"text":"Frontal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postcentral gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Olfactory cortex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Limbus system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporal lobe","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16512,"text":"In which of the following situations does one get the greatest depth of focus?","explanation":"The greatest depth of focus is achieved with an **extremely small size of pupil**. The depth of focus refers to the range over which objects can be seen clearly without changing the focus of the eye. A smaller pupil size creates a pinhole effect, which increases the depth of focus. When the pupil is very small, more rays of light are parallel as they enter the eye, reducing the need for precise focusing by the lens and thereby increasing the depth of focus.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the contraction of the ciliary muscle and the relaxation of the ciliary muscle are involved in the accommodation process, changing the shape of the lens to focus light on the retina, but they do not inherently increase the depth of focus. In a dark environment or with a large pupil, the depth of focus decreases because a larger pupil allows more divergent rays of light to enter the eye, requiring more precise focusing by the lens.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 632.","responses":[{"text":"Extremely small size of pupil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of ciliary muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large pupil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relaxation of ciliary muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In dark environment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16514,"text":"Which protein is responsible for absorbing light in the retina and for vision?","explanation":"**Rhodopsin** is the protein responsible for absorbing light in the retina and is essential for the process of vision. It plays a central role in phototransduction, the conversion of light stimuli into electrical signals that are sent to the brain for visual perception.\r\n\r\nRhodopsin consists of two main components: a protein called **opsin** and a molecule of **11-cis-retinal**, which is a form of vitamin A (retinaldehyde). When light enters the eye and strikes the retina, it is absorbed by rhodopsin. This absorption leads to a conformational change in the 11-cis-retinal molecule, converting it into **all-trans-retinal**. This change in retinal structure triggers a cascade of biochemical events, ultimately generating electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain through the optic nerve, allowing us to perceive visual information.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 641.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Melanin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhodopsin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16519,"text":"Which biochemical form of vitamin A is found in the visual cycle?","explanation":"In the visual cycle, the biochemical form of vitamin A that plays a crucial role is **Retinaldehyde**. This form of vitamin A is essential for the process of phototransduction, which occurs in the retina of the eye and is responsible for the conversion of light into nerve signals that are transmitted to the brain, ultimately allowing us to see.\r\n\r\nWhen light strikes the retina, it is absorbed by the pigment molecule called **rhodopsin**, which consists of a protein called opsin and a molecule of **11-cis-retinal**, a form of retinaldehyde. Upon absorbing light, 11-cis-retinal is converted into **all-trans-retinal**, which triggers a series of molecular events leading to the generation of electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain, allowing us to perceive visual information.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 497.","responses":[{"text":"Retinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinyl ester","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinaldehyde","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16520,"text":"What disease is caused by the deficiency of vitamin A?","explanation":"A deficiency of **vitamin A** is primarily responsible for causing **xerophthalmia**, which is a condition characterized by dryness and damage to the eyes. Vitamin A is essential for maintaining healthy vision and the proper functioning of the eye.\r\n\r\nWhen there is a deficiency of vitamin A, the eye's ability to produce tears and maintain the mucous membranes on the surface of the eye is compromised. This can lead to symptoms such as dryness, night blindness, and, if left untreated, can progress to more severe issues like corneal damage and blindness.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Strabismus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amblyopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xeropthalmia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glaucoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16521,"text":"A team of doctors needs to know the exact source of intestinal bleeding in a patient. They radiolabeled (and radioactive atoms) a sample of red blood cells taken from a patient. They then reinject the blood to follow the path of blood in the patient. Which of the following technique is used?","explanation":"When doctors need to pinpoint the exact source of intestinal bleeding in a patient, they utilize a **SPECT (Single Photon Emission Computed Tomography) scan**. This imaging technique involves radiolabeling red blood cells with radioactive atoms and then reinjecting them into the patient's bloodstream. The radiolabeled blood cells follow the path of blood flow within the body, allowing for the identification of the source of bleeding.\r\n\r\nSPECT scans are particularly valuable in assessing blood flow and perfusion in different organs and tissues. They provide three-dimensional images with high specificity, making them well-suited for situations like this where the goal is to locate the origin of bleeding accurately.","reference":"Yandrapalli S, Puckett Y. SPECT imaging. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 2, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564426/","responses":[{"text":"X ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SPECT scan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16522,"text":"A professor was comparing nuclear medicine with conventional radiology. Among the following, which is a characteristic feature of nuclear medicine procedure?","explanation":"Nuclear medicine procedures are characterized by the use of **radioactive materials**, also known as radiopharmaceuticals, which are either **injected, ingested, or inhaled** by the patient. These radiopharmaceuticals contain a radioactive isotope and are chosen based on their affinity for specific organs or tissues. \r\n\r\nDuring a nuclear medicine procedure, the radiopharmaceutical is taken up by the target tissue, where it emits gamma rays. These gamma rays are detected by a gamma camera or other imaging devices, allowing for the visualization of both the **structure and function** of the organ or tissue under examination.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, conventional radiology typically involves the use of X-rays, where **beams of radiation pass through the body** to create images primarily focused on **anatomical structure**. Nuclear medicine, on the other hand, provides valuable information about **functional aspects** of organs or tissues in addition to their structure. It is also utilized for both diagnosis and monitoring of various medical conditions.","reference":"Nuclear medicine. National Institute of Biomedical Imaging and Bioengineering. Accessed July 2, 2023. https://www.nibib.nih.gov/science-education/science-topics/nuclear-medicine","responses":[{"text":"Cannot elaborate upon body functions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shows structure only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beams of radiation pass through the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioactive material is injected, ingested, or inhaled","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mainly used in diagnosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16523,"text":"A patient intends to seek advice for his forthcoming travel tour to Kenya. He visits the clinic for advice on vaccination, precautions, and chemoprophylaxis. Among the following, which branch of medicine deals specifically with the patient's queries?","explanation":"The patient's inquiries regarding vaccinations, precautions, and chemoprophylaxis for their travel to Kenya fall under the purview of **emporiatrics**. Emporiatrics is a specialized branch of medicine that deals specifically with the health concerns of travelers. It focuses on providing medical advice and preventive measures to individuals traveling to different regions, taking into account the specific health risks associated with their destination.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **infectious diseases** primarily focuses on the diagnosis and management of infectious diseases, while **epidemiology** is the study of the patterns and causes of health-related events within populations. **Geriatrics** and **geriatric medicine** are concerned with the healthcare of elderly individuals.","reference":"Oberoi SS. Emporiatrics: The growing area of concern. Journal of Research in Medical Sciences : The Official Journal of Isfahan University of Medical Sciences. Published September 2014. Accessed July 2, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4268184/","responses":[{"text":"Geriatrics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emporiatrics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infectious diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Geriatric medicine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16558,"text":"A 50-year-old man comes to the outpatient department with the feeling as if he was floating or if the world was spinning. The affected nerve responsible for this condition receives motor sensation from which of the following?","explanation":"In the case of this patient experiencing a feeling of floating or spinning, the affected nerve responsible for this sensation is likely the **vestibular nerve**, which is a component of the **vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII)**. The vestibular nerve carries sensory information related to **balance, spatial orientation, and head position**.\r\n\r\nThe **vestibule** is a part of the inner ear and contains two important structures, the **utricle and saccule**. These structures are responsible for detecting changes in **linear acceleration and head position**. They play a significant role in providing sensory input to the vestibular nerve.\r\n\r\nThe **semicircular canals** are also part of the inner ear, but they are primarily responsible for detecting **angular acceleration and rotational head movements** rather than the sensation of floating or spinning.\r\n\r\nThe **cochlea** is involved in **hearing** and not related to the patient's complaint of feeling unsteady.","reference":"Balance disorders — causes, types \u0026 treatment | nidcd. Published March 6, 2018. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/balance-disorders","responses":[{"text":"Cochlea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saccule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Semicircular canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Utricle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16559,"text":"A patient comes to the family physician with a complaint of pain in the temporomandibular joint that gets worse during the opening of the mouth. After examination and investigation, diagnosis of forward dislocation of mandible is made. Which factor does not normally oppose the forward movement of this bone?","explanation":"In the case of forward dislocation of the mandible, the primary factor responsible for the condition is the lack of opposition from the **lateral pterygoid muscle**. This muscle has two heads, the superior and inferior heads. The superior head plays a crucial role in initiating the forward movement of the mandible, while the inferior head functions as a depressor of the mandible.\r\n\r\nThe **temporalis muscle**, particularly its posterior fibers, is responsible for closing the jaw and opposes the forward movement of the mandible. The **medial pterygoid** and **masseter muscles** also contribute to the closure of the jaw and provide resistance against the forward dislocation.\r\n\r\nThe **articular eminence**, on the other hand, is a bony feature of the temporal bone that helps guide the mandibular condyle during movements but does not actively oppose forward movement.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporalis (posterior fibres)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Articular eminence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16573,"text":"The presynaptic parasympathetic fibers to the otic ganglion in the infratemporal fossa are carried by which of the following nerve?","explanation":"The presynaptic parasympathetic fibers that target the otic ganglion in the infratemporal fossa are carried by the **lesser petrosal nerve**. This anatomical pathway is an essential component of the parasympathetic innervation of the salivary glands, specifically the parotid gland.\r\n\r\nThe lesser petrosal nerve originates from the **glossopharyngeal nerve (cranial nerve IX)** and carries the preganglionic parasympathetic fibers that synapse in the otic ganglion. From there, postganglionic fibers continue to the parotid gland, where they stimulate salivary secretion.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 971.","responses":[{"text":"Carotid sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep petrosal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser petrosal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater petrosal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16575,"text":"Involuntary fixation is the ability to keep a selected object in your visual field once it has been found via a combination of drifting and flickering movements. Which of the following is most responsible for the loss of this ability?","explanation":"Involuntary fixation is a crucial component of visual processing, allowing us to maintain focus on a selected object. The **superior colliculus** plays a pivotal role in this process. It is a paired structure located in the midbrain, specifically in the tectum of the mesencephalon. The Superior colliculus is primarily responsible for the coordination of **eye movements** and the orientation of our gaze towards **relevant stimuli** in the environment.\r\n\r\nWhen we identify an object in our visual field, the superior colliculus helps to keep it in focus through a combination of mechanisms involving rapid **drifting and flickering movements of the eyes**. This ability to maintain fixation on a chosen object is crucial for visual tracking and engagement with our surroundings.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 659.","responses":[{"text":"Superior colliculus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior colliculus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial longitudinal fasciculus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear nerve nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior colliculus muscle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16576,"text":"Which of the following pupillary responses is seen in the Argyll Robertson pupil?","explanation":"The Argyll Robertson pupil is a unique pupillary abnormality often associated with neurosyphilis, particularly in its late stages. This condition is characterized by specific pupillary responses. In the case of an Argyll Robertson pupil, the affected pupil fails to constrict in response to light, which means it does not get smaller when exposed to a bright light source.\r\n\r\nHowever, what sets it apart from other pupillary abnormalities is that the Argyll Robertson pupil still responds to accommodation. Accommodation is the reflex that allows the eye to adjust its focus for near vision by changing the shape of the lens. When a person with an Argyll Robertson pupil attempts to focus on a near object, the affected pupil will constrict, demonstrating its ability to accommodate.\r\n\r\nThis unique combination of **failure to respond to light** and **normal response to accommodation** is a hallmark of the Argyll Robertson pupil and is often indicative of underlying neurological issues, particularly neurosyphilis.","reference":"Dichter SL, Shubert GS. Argyll robertson pupil. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed July 3, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537179/","responses":[{"text":"Failure to respond to accommodation but responds to light","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal response to light and accommodation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure to respond to accommodation only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure to respond to both accommodation and light","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure to respond to light but responds to accommodation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16579,"text":"How many times as much force is applied to the cochlear fluid as applied to the tympanic membrane by sound waves?","explanation":"In the process of sound transmission through the ear, sound waves are initially captured by the tympanic membrane, commonly known as the eardrum. This delicate membrane serves as a barrier that separates the external auditory canal from the middle ear. When sound waves strike the tympanic membrane, they generate vibrations, causing it to move inward and outward. \r\n\r\nThese vibrations are then transferred to the three small auditory ossicles in the middle ear: the malleus, incus, and stapes. The stapes, in particular, is attached to the oval window, which is the entrance to the inner ear's fluid-filled cochlea.\r\n\r\nThe oval window acts as a hydraulic amplifier, concentrating the force applied by the stapes onto the cochlear fluid. This amplification results in a force that is **22 times greater** when applied to the cochlear fluid compared to the force originally applied to the tympanic membrane by sound waves. This amplification allows the auditory system to efficiently transmit and convert sound energy into electrical signals that can be processed by the brain, contributing to our ability to hear sounds of varying intensities.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 664.","responses":[{"text":"17 folds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 folds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.3 folds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"22 folds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"55 folds","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

